Inflation in Europe jumps because of food
Accelerating inflation measured in the euro area is mainly due to steady increases in food prices.
Price growth in November in 13 eurozone countries was higher than expected, up from 2.6 per cent in October with an annual inflation rate of 3.1 per cent, the Luxembourg Statistical Office of the Union said.
The official forecast was only 3 percent, Bloomberg said.
Unlike the U.S., British and Canadian issuing banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the basic interest rate, with the fall along with rising commodity prices and falling unemployment leading to an inflation spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below 2%, but close to them.
According to one of the analysts, the ECB is in an absurd situation: it has to "advertise" inflation so that it does not have to do anything about it later.
In Germany, November inflation represents a record 3.3 per cent for 15 years, while in Spain it rose from 3.6 per cent to 4.1 per cent.
Inflation in the euro area has erupted upwards due to sharply rising food and energy prices.
The futures prices of wheat rose by 88 percent, and the price of soybeans reached its highest value since 1973.
Similarly, in 2007 it was necessary to pay significantly more for edible oil and dairy products.
The price of oil in the world markets this year rose by 52 percent and last month already cost one barrel of black gold nearly $ 100.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump in 2008 from 2.1 percent this year to 2.5, but in 2009 it will already fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, the level of 12-month inflation in the next 3-4 months will remain at approximately 3%, but its average annual rate will be 2.1%.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to cut interest rates twice as soon as possible during 2008.
