In many places, it saves on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand cases of infection have been registered in hospitals, mainly due to the inappropriate use of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, overcrowding of beds, overload of staff stopping diseases do not help, says the Mayor of the National Epidemiological Center.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
Recently, MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of St. John’s Hospital.
Bacteria resistant to antibiotics were found in a man who was hospitalized after a serious car accident.
The patient was isolated.
A similar infection occurred in the same place at the beginning of the year.
A patient injured in a serious car accident was released home, but not long afterwards he had to return with MRSA infection and because of the bacteria in his body, one important operation could not be performed.
As of December 10, 1,094 hospital infections caused by multidrug-resistant pathogens have been reported to the National Nesocomialis Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröczová, Mayor of the National Epidemiological Center.
This means that so many infections caused by multidrug-resistant pathogens have been registered in hospitals with certainty, others are not known.
Nearly two-thirds (683) of infections were caused by MRSA, or methicillin-oxacillin resistant gold staphylococcus.
Staphylococcus aureus (SA) is carried by one-third of people in the nose without causing the disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. throat inflammation, tonsillitis, skin infections, morning infections) respond well to antibiotics and can be treated well.
However, if the antibiotic is given excessively or inappropriately, it develops from a bacterium that responds well to antibiotics, a bacterium that is very resistant to antibiotics and that spreads rapidly in inappropriate hospital conditions.
Especially in the case of temporary or permanent malfunction of the immune system in patients with a weakened body, low body weight or in patients in years can cause serious hospital infections, for example, morning infection or blood poisoning - sepsis.
According to St. John’s Hospital’s top doctor, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, similar infections are part of daily practice in hospitals.
"Infection should not be confused with epidemic, MRSA is not just there," said Tibor Nyulasi, "where the presence of the disease is not being investigated."
Resistant to antibiotics
“We are isolating these patients, treating them in rubber gloves and masks, and we have the necessary antibiotics to treat them,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients admitted to the hospital are first examined to see if MRSA is present in their body, but infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling is not in fashion
The vast majority of hospital infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but current conditions and conditions in home hospitals are not favorable for preventing the emergence and spread of multidrug-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröczová.
Because this infection occurs typically in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should monitor patients admitted and isolate MRSA carriers immediately.
However, the collection of microbiological samples in Hungarian hospitals is not in fashion.
It also plays a role in the fact that the National Health Insurance Fund does not fund these examinations.
The majority of cases are detected if the patient suffers from a perceptible MRSA infection, said the mayor of the epidemiological center.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the appropriate treatment of antibiotics in the field of human medicine and there are also domestic directives for the treatment of individual infections, diseases.
Efforts should be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, or microbiological testing should be carried out to prevent the development of drug resistance, but even hospitals do not comply with this in all cases.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in primary and outpatient treatment of patients, Karolina Böröczová said.
Savings on disinfectants
According to scientific evidence, MRSA spreads among patients most often through healthcare professionals.
Therefore, hand washing and the use of gloves and masks play a very important role, but even in this there are serious shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection and touch, but it is not always possible to isolate infected patients in the conditions of home hospitals.
On the contrary, the rooms are often crowded, the beds are often very close to each other, although from an epidemiological point of view, patients should be at least 1.5 meters away from each other.
As Karolina Böröczová pointed out, unfortunately, we can also see that in hospitals in a materially disadvantaged situation, disinfectants are saved, there are few nurses and many patients, which increases the chance of infection.
According to Karolina Böröcz, where the necessary protective measures are observed, similar infections are demonstrably less or the further spread of the cause of the disease can be stopped.
Government Program Against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA is a huge expense for health insurance companies and is being fought against everywhere.
For example, in England, the government has written a program to prevent MRSA, or to reduce its incidence.
The program appears to be successful, according to published data, MRSA infections in England are showing a decreasing trend.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) ranks prevention of multi-resistance pathogens (including MRSA) and hospital infections caused by these pathogens among its priorities.
