Political Capital: The Hungarian Guard increased the risk of the country
The activity of the Hungarian Guard, founded with the support of the Jobbik Magyarországért movement in August this year, according to the Risk Analysis Division of the Political Capital Institute, increased the political risk of Hungary and the entire region in several respects.
The company's "risk alert" states that the greatest political risk in connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard is that "the concentration of already existing ethnic tensions between the Roma and non-Roma populations of Hungary can occur in a short time, even with violent ethnicity".
The main reason is that the political strategy of the Hungarian Guard is probably aimed at provoking such an action - adds the research institute.
As he writes, all this can be explained by one of the biggest negligence of Hungarian political officials: "The public debate on the Roma issue was left by representatives of public life to representatives of radical and extremist political groups, who could build a political strategy on the Roma-Hungarian contradiction."
This deepens the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, strengthens extremists and increases the likelihood of violent conflicts - the institute judges.
In addition, the activity of the Hungarian Guard, according to the research institute, due to the great attention of domestic and foreign media, "has greatly distorted the image of Hungary abroad, especially in terms of the belief in the stability of the country and its democratic development".
The Institute recalls: as part of the reorganization of Hungarian radical and ultra-rightist groups, which has been gaining more and more publicity and vehemence since the fall of 2006, it is the fact that in Hungary since the summer of 2007 several organizations have been created, which they call themselves associations of "national defense".
"The common feature of these groups is that they define themselves as civil associations, while openly declaring - even armed - the readiness of their members to perform defensive tasks (in the case of natural disasters, attacks on the homeland, disturbances of the order), in addition to the state, with a reference to the incompetence of the police.
It also notes: all this is done in a way that tries to wrap various political efforts built on the resistance of society to politics and parties in civilian clothes.
The emphasis on civility and the form of the association in the case of these groups therefore serves not only to avoid legal obstacles to judicial registration, but is also a political strategy.
