The holidays are not free everywhere.
In Hungary, the holidays are precisely set by law and it has become a common practice that working days are moved around the holidays, which is expected to happen less often next year.
The holidays are not uniform in the European Union or in the United States.
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes national and national holidays and days of rest.
The days of quiet work are mostly related to church holidays or important historical events.
We also celebrate the New Year: the last day of the old year and the first day of the new year is work holiday - on New Year's Day so that people can rest after New Year's Eve.
There are eleven free holidays throughout the year.
The national holiday is March 15, celebrating the Revolution of 1848 and October 23, commemorating the Revolution of 1956.
On the 20th of August we celebrate the founding of the state, on the 1st of May work, on the 1st and 2nd of November we commemorate the deceased relatives and friends.
In addition, we have two-day holidays of Easter, Anniversary and Christmas.
Since our national, national or religious holidays rarely coincide with the weekend, it has become a practice to move the working day in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
The price for extended weekends, however, is that we stay in the workplace and at school on the previous Saturdays.
The day immediately preceding or following the holiday, which we work on, has been regulated by the Minister of Labour in a special decree for many years.
The legislation applies equally to all employers and employees employed by them, to public servants and to persons in the public service.
However, it does not apply to companies and institutions that are in operation without interruption or with regard to their destination, even on working days of rest.
This year, there will be a change in the working order only around the end of the year: from December 24, life in the country will almost stop, because according to previous experience, most people will "work" in advance of the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve or will thus take advantage of the saved holidays.
Next year, a few of our holidays fall in the middle, respectively at the end of the week, so the shifts of the working day will be less than this year.
For the first time, the calendar is changed around the holiday of work, so that the workers can then stay at home for four days of taste.
Saturday 26 April will be a working day, so that Friday 2 May can be a day of rest.
The next move is related to the holiday of October 23: on Saturday, October 18, work will be done instead of Friday, October 24.
At the end of the year, however, next year will be able to take place completely in the sign of the holidays, because from December 24, they will have nonstop holidays almost everywhere, even though New Year’s Eve falls on Wednesday.
