In the end, failure.
Serbian and Kosovo Albanians ended the sixth and final round of talks on Wednesday morning in Baden, Austria, without being able to overcome divergent views on the future status of the separatist province.
"It is regrettable that both sides have not been able to reach a status agreement," European negotiator Wolfgang Ischinger said at a press conference in Vienna.
His American counterpart, Frank Wisner, stressed that peace in the area is "at stake" and called on Belgrade and Pristina to take care of their commitments to maintain peace and be ready for dialogue even after the negotiations are over.
"We do not expect violence in the near future, but we are entering a difficult period," he added, adding that "it is obvious that the situation is tense."
