Americans and Europeans expect the talks to end on December 10.
On the other hand, the Russians, who previously blocked Kosovo’s independence in the UN Security Council, insist that the talks continue beyond this deadline.
"Russia has been and remains in favour of a negotiated, compromised solution," Bocan-Charchenko said.
A unilateral declaration of independence?
After eight years of administration by the international community, the West sees Kosovo’s independence under EU supervision as the only viable solution.
Pristina declares that if the Security Council does not decide in its favour, it is ready to declare independence unilaterally.
Belgrade insists on expanded autonomy.
"Unfortunately, we have not reached any agreement," Kosovo's President Fatmir Sejdiu said at a hotel in Baden, where the "last chance of negotiations" had been held since Monday.
Hashim Thaçi, a former rebel commander of Kosovo Albanians and future prime minister of the province, expressed regret.
However, he added that the autonomy plan presented by Belgrade "belongs to the past, which has led to murders and deportations".
