Serbian President Boris Tadic, on the other hand, believes that the compromise is still being considered and warned the Albanian majority in Kosovo of the consequences of the province's unilaterally declared independence.
Belgrade is particularly concerned about the "dominance effect" in the area, which is still unstable as a result of the wars of independence in the 1990s.
"But that does not mean for Serbia," he said, "that a compromise is impossible."
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation insisted that all decisions should belong exclusively to the Security Council, in which its Russian ally has the right to veto.
