Two months ago, when the prime minister avoided calling elections and insulted British intelligence by claiming that the decision was not influenced by the polls, there was hope that it would secure a resilient and effective government.
Instead, as the increasingly funny Liberal Democrat deputy leader put it, the once feared Mr. Brown changed from Stalin to Mr. Bean.
The ruthless rescue of the troubled Northern Rock bank showed weaknesses in driving and poor judgment under fire.
Poorly thought-out proposals to change the tax code have brought companies together against the government.
The loss of personal data in 25 million people revealed unimaginable administrative laziness.
A trio of retired generals started a rebellion in the House of Lords; they protested against cuts in military spending, claiming that being a commander of the armed forces is part-time work.
Now there are multilingual gifts from David Abrahams; Peter Watt, the general secretary of the Labour (and their former guardian of internal discipline), has already resigned.
None of this means that Mr. Brown is inevitably heading towards his end.
Nevertheless, governments can reach a tipping point at which they find governance difficult.
People don’t trust politicians and don’t like them, but most of the time they put aside their mistrust when a new party takes over.
When it seems clear that some prime minister is unlikely to improve anything, and may not be in office for a long time, this is the push away: the state administration becomes punchy, the ministers begin to do briefings, the press looks for bad news, and the government becomes unfocused and defensive.
In one sense, Mr Brown's position is particularly complex, as he cannot take the position of a new skeleton compared to other political leaders.
As much as he wanted to distance himself from Tony Blair, he was his first officer.
For example, problems with Northern Rock and the Treasury records are linked to the decisions Mr. Brown made as Treasury Secretary.
And while he wasn’t directly involved in Blair’s troubles, such as the long investigation into political party funding caused by “value for money,” voters can safely conclude that he was.
Still, Mr. Brown's troubles aren't as bad as they look.
They're not as bad as the conservatives do.
As far as Mr. Bean is concerned, no one has died or been misled.
And the cure, as painful as it may be, is to provide what Mr. Brown’s Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable, firm, and slightly brutal government.
The latest turmoil around political gifts is a good example.
Garboid Mr. Abrahams, who compares his gifts to charity, says he did not want any publicity for his charity.
That may be true, but the decision was not his.
Laws against the anonymity of big political donors are clear and exist for a simple reason: the public has the right to know who could buy access to those who rule the country.
Mr. Watt, who said he knew about Mr. Abrahams's actions but did not know that they were illegal, will certainly be thoroughly questioned; as will Jon Mendlesohn, the main Labour money-seeker, who learned about the mischievous donations in October.
But Mr. Brown is not involved yet; there is nothing to suggest that he knew about these skins, even though most of the payments were made only after his appearance in June.
The Prime Minister has done half the work.
Very quickly he condemned this violation of the laws by his own party, but he diluted his determination by reaching out for a proven instrument, a commission to investigate the matter - led by a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, the lessons are not complicated.
If the law has been violated, it is a matter for the police.
In addition, there are other things Mr Brown has to do, such as finding a permanent chairman of the independent Committee on Standards in Public Life, which has not had one for six months, and moving forward with a real reform of political party funding.
That would require Labourers who are in a tight spot to cooperate with the Conservatives and perhaps even give up their special financial relationship with the unions - bitter pills for a committed party like Mr Brown.
But he should face a few simple facts.
The Conservatives now have a decent lead in the polls; he has two years to win back the voters; and the only way to win is unassailable integrity and high competence.
