Does the mortgage crisis affect the U.S. credit card market?
When there is blood in the water, the spinal cords naturally begin to agitate.
Now that the U.S. real estate market is shrinking, predators have focused on the credit card market there.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs say losses on credit cards could reach $99 billion if other variants of consumer loans become infected by inferior mortgages.
The signs of tension are obvious.
There is an increase in the number of cases of inability to repay (with more than 30-day payment delays) and depreciation of accounts (accounts that the provider considers unenforceable).
HSBC Bank announced last month that it had lost $1.4 billion in the U.S. consumer credit market – also due to insolvent credit card loans.
It is still too early to panic.
Accounts depreciated and inability to pay are still few.
According to the Moody’s rating agency, the 3.89% insolvency rate in the third quarter was almost an entire percentage point below average.
The deteriorating rates can be partly explained by technical reasons.
The change in the U.S. Personal Insolvency Act of 2005 led to a sharp drop in the number of reported bankruptcies, which make up a large part of the losses on credit cards; thus, the number of reports (and thus the number of write-offs) would increase regardless of whether or not the general conditions for lenders deteriorated.
The industry also has a good maturity rate, which shows how much consumers pay off their debts monthly.
And the confidence in the securities of secured credit cards is strong, despite the paralysis in other corners of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney of the TowerGroup research firm predicts that their emissions for 2007 will be 25% higher than last year.
Direct pathways for spreading infection between the mortgage crisis and the credit card market definitely exist: when real estate loans are dried up, consumers are more likely to indebted via credit cards.
However, credit card issuers tend to look at the cash flow rather than the value of guarantors, so falling home prices may not necessarily mean a change in the creditworthiness of lenders.
They can even be beneficial for loan providers.
Consumers’ motivation to repay mortgages decreases when the value of their assets falls below the value of the loan; as a result, card debt moves up on the priority list for repayment.
Card issuers will also be able to respond to more turbulent conditions faster and more flexibly than mortgage providers by changing interest rates or debt limits.
This should theoretically reduce the risks of rapid changes in the prices of guarantors.
“It won’t happen that we would just reassess all the loans one beautiful morning,” says Gary Perlin, chief financial officer at Capital One.
