These aren't Warhol's boxes.
The person who combines Sweden and wooden boxes doesn’t think of Andy Warhol, but of Ikea.
Or is it?
Wooden boxes currently produced in Sweden cast Warhol’s dark shadows on the list.
Most of his list of ninety-four "Brillo boxes" of the Stockholm type are fakes.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" a few months ago expressed doubts about the authenticity of Warhol's "Brillo boxes" in 1968, the internal research of the Moderna Museet in Stockholm comes with a result that brought disappointment; the six "Brillo boxes" which in 1995 were dedicated to the Moderna Museet Museum - the "Brillo boxes" of the Moderna Museet
Previous events are a messy, confusing chain of artistic and curatorial events.
Warhol made his first Brillo boxes in New York City in 1964, painting wooden boxes that were based on the red-blue-white design of Brillo soap-powder paper boxes.
The exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968 showed - with Warhol's consent - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard. These were not (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo factory.
It was not about works of art, but about their masterpieces, just exhibition pieces.
Warhol apparently also gave permission in 1968 to make several wooden Brillo buckets in Sweden, but these are not exhibited in the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses at the time are now talking about fifteen boxes that then rightfully entered art and auction history as authorized originals - "Andy Warhol's Brillo Boxy" with the designation Typ Stockholm.
Some of them were auctioned for more than $100,000.
The problem now lies in the fact that the legendary director of the museum Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that about a hundred coffins were made and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, 105 Hulten beds were made in Malmö for the St. Petersburg exhibition in 1990.
At that time, Warhol was already three years after his death.
In addition to the six Brillo boxes owned by the museum, Lars Byström, the top conservator of Moderna Museet, also examined three Brillo boxes from a Swedish private collection, two of which were made in Sweden in 1968 and after their plywood panels were painted with plywood and base bars.
On the contrary, from the structure of the copies from 1990, it appeared that the paint was applied directly to the plywood board by a paint roll without a previous base coating - besides, it is an acrylic and not an oil paint.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from Warhol's official Brillo boxes list," Lars Nittve, director of Moderna Museet, said: "If the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board doesn't come up with a six-pointer in New York, Moderna will come up with a six-pointer."
In July, the Authentication Board announced that it would deal with these "critical allegations" made in the case of soap boxes.
The organization, however, remains in relentless silence.
